Bellman-Ford Algorithm
What problem does it solve?

Find shortest distance from a source node to all other nodes.

Unlike Dijkstra:

✅ Works with negative edge weights
✅ Can detect negative cycles

MAIN IDEA--> Bellman-Ford simply relaxes every edge repeatedly.

Relaxation

Suppose edge:

u ----wt----> v

If

dist[u] + wt < dist[v]

then

dist[v] = dist[u] + wt;

This is called relaxing an edge. Therefore: If we relax all edges V - 1 times all shortest distances are guaranteed to be found.

######  Most Important Observation  #####

In a graph with V vertices:

Shortest path can contain at most

V - 1 edges

Why?

Because if a path uses V edges, some node repeats.
That forms a cycle.
Removing cycle gives a shorter/equal path.

Detection Trick

After doing: V-1 relaxations, do one extra relaxation.

If any distance still decreases:

dist[u] + wt < dist[v]

then

Negative Cycle Exists

ALGORITHM-->
dist[src] = 0

Repeat V-1 times:
    Relax every edge

One extra pass:
    If any edge relaxes
       Negative Cycle

Hence,
TIME-- O(V*E)
Space:O(V)

CODE-> 
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> bellmanFord(int V,vector<vector<int>>& edges,int src) {

        vector<int> dist(V, 1e8);
        dist[src] = 0;

        // V-1 relaxations
        for(int i = 0; i < V - 1; i++) {

            for(auto &it : edges) {

                int u = it[0];
                int v = it[1];
                int wt = it[2];

                if(dist[u] != 1e8 && dist[u] + wt < dist[v]) { //relaxtion

                    dist[v] = dist[u] + wt;
                }
            }
        }

        // Negative cycle check
        for(auto &it : edges) {

            int u = it[0];
            int v = it[1];
            int wt = it[2];

            if(dist[u] != 1e8 && dist[u] + wt < dist[v]) {

                return {-1};
            }
        }

        return dist;
    }
};
